1
00:00:06,166 --> 00:00:08,375
[Varee panting]

2
00:00:08,458 --> 00:00:11,833
[foreboding music playing]

3
00:00:12,750 --> 00:00:13,583
Min?

4
00:00:16,666 --> 00:00:18,041
Min, are you in here?

5
00:00:18,125 --> 00:00:20,125
[ghostly whoosh]

6
00:00:33,791 --> 00:00:35,333
- [Min yells]
- [Varee screams]

7
00:00:35,416 --> 00:00:37,416
[loud thudding]

8
00:00:38,083 --> 00:00:39,208
[cell phone vibrating]

9
00:00:40,333 --> 00:00:43,708
[clock ticking]

10
00:00:43,791 --> 00:00:46,375
[electricity crackling]

11
00:00:50,166 --> 00:00:53,375
1991

12
00:00:53,458 --> 00:00:55,916
Have you packed a towel
and a change of fresh clothes?

13
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:58,541
You'll need them
after you have swum in the sea.

14
00:00:58,625 --> 00:01:01,000
Yes, and I'm going to bring
all my new toys with me.

15
00:01:01,083 --> 00:01:02,291
[phone ringing]

16
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:05,708
[TV reporter speaking indistinctly]

17
00:01:06,375 --> 00:01:09,541
- [phone continues ringing]
- Aon, finish Varee's hair for me.

18
00:01:10,541 --> 00:01:13,916
[reporter on TV] The Prime Minister
is prepared to take an oath of allegiance…

19
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:14,833
Hello?

20
00:01:14,916 --> 00:01:16,750
…before His Majesty the King…

21
00:01:17,916 --> 00:01:19,583
How did it happen?

22
00:01:19,666 --> 00:01:21,916
[reporter] …in a C130 transport aircraft…

23
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:23,500
[sighs] Okay.

24
00:01:23,583 --> 00:01:26,208
Tell everyone to stay put. I'm on my way.

25
00:01:27,250 --> 00:01:31,083
[reporter] It is Saturday,
the 23rd of February, 1991.

26
00:01:31,166 --> 00:01:32,000
All set?

27
00:01:32,708 --> 00:01:34,833
Let's head off before it gets too hot.

28
00:01:35,333 --> 00:01:38,000
There's a problem at the plant.
They need me there.

29
00:01:38,500 --> 00:01:40,083
[reporter] On this historic day,

30
00:01:40,166 --> 00:01:44,375
the army has seized power
in a coup d'état led by General Sunthorn

31
00:01:44,458 --> 00:01:46,333
of the National Peacekeeping Council.

32
00:01:48,625 --> 00:01:49,458
[sighs]

33
00:01:49,541 --> 00:01:52,083
[gentle music playing]

34
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:01,333
[sighs]

35
00:02:09,083 --> 00:02:10,541
Natee, get the car.

36
00:02:11,333 --> 00:02:13,541
Mr. Wat and Miss Varee are not coming?

37
00:02:14,458 --> 00:02:16,500
The beach is off. Take me to the plant.

38
00:02:20,708 --> 00:02:22,333
[engine turns over]

39
00:02:22,916 --> 00:02:25,291
[melancholy music playing]

40
00:02:25,375 --> 00:02:27,916
Mom, where are you going?

41
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:29,458
Mom, don't go!

42
00:02:29,541 --> 00:02:30,375
[Wat] Varee!

43
00:02:32,083 --> 00:02:32,916
[sighs]

44
00:02:34,375 --> 00:02:35,750
It's okay, dear.

45
00:02:36,250 --> 00:02:37,666
We'll go to the beach later.

46
00:02:51,583 --> 00:02:54,375
[reporter on radio] Reports to hand
indicate there were five main reasons

47
00:02:54,458 --> 00:02:57,708
for seizing and controlling
the administrative power of the country

48
00:02:57,791 --> 00:03:00,083
- and carrying out the coup d'état…
- Natee, turn it off.

49
00:03:00,166 --> 00:03:02,416
- …on February 23rd, 1991.
- Yes, ma'am.

50
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:03,375
[radio turns off]

51
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:11,000
[pensive music playing]

52
00:03:18,166 --> 00:03:20,375
RESTRICTED AREA

53
00:03:26,916 --> 00:03:29,458
The electrical voltage is very unstable.

54
00:03:29,541 --> 00:03:31,250
It drops when we run the machine.

55
00:03:31,333 --> 00:03:33,750
[alarm blaring]

56
00:03:33,833 --> 00:03:35,833
[metallic clanking]

57
00:03:36,833 --> 00:03:39,791
Shut down the whole system.
Begin to run a test series.

58
00:03:39,875 --> 00:03:41,333
Let's see what happens then.

59
00:03:44,083 --> 00:03:46,583
[woman on PA] All personnel,
please make preparations.

60
00:03:46,666 --> 00:03:49,291
We are commencing test number 36 now.

61
00:03:50,041 --> 00:03:52,750
- [gear clanks]
- [engines whirring]

62
00:03:55,583 --> 00:03:57,041
[metal grinding loudly]

63
00:03:57,125 --> 00:03:58,208
[ominous music playing]

64
00:04:01,416 --> 00:04:03,416
[electricity crackling]

65
00:04:07,833 --> 00:04:09,833
[foreboding music playing]

66
00:04:22,208 --> 00:04:24,708
- [electricity crackling]
- [wind whistling]

67
00:04:34,333 --> 00:04:35,708
[engines power down]

68
00:04:35,791 --> 00:04:37,791
[alarm blaring]

69
00:04:48,291 --> 00:04:49,125
[music stops]

70
00:04:55,583 --> 00:04:56,500
[young Varee] Mom!

71
00:04:58,250 --> 00:05:00,625
Varee, go back to bed.

72
00:05:00,708 --> 00:05:01,666
I have to work.

73
00:05:06,625 --> 00:05:09,875
[tender piano music playing]

74
00:05:13,458 --> 00:05:15,333
Why did you throw the book like that?

75
00:05:20,125 --> 00:05:22,875
What's wrong, sweetie? Tell me.

76
00:05:24,458 --> 00:05:26,458
Mom didn't want to read me the story.

77
00:05:26,541 --> 00:05:28,583
She broke her promise again.

78
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:31,375
Show me the story.

79
00:05:32,083 --> 00:05:32,916
I'll read it.

80
00:05:38,166 --> 00:05:40,541
This is the new book Mom bought.

81
00:05:40,625 --> 00:05:41,750
Write your name in it.

82
00:05:51,625 --> 00:05:54,416
VAREE

83
00:05:55,916 --> 00:05:57,208
Varee.

84
00:05:57,875 --> 00:05:59,041
[chuckles tenderly]

85
00:06:04,166 --> 00:06:05,625
[glass shatters in distance]

86
00:06:10,166 --> 00:06:12,166
[tense music playing]

87
00:06:21,666 --> 00:06:26,291
[Wat] Have you forgotten
how hard it was for us to have this child?

88
00:06:27,250 --> 00:06:29,166
[mother] So what do you want me to do?

89
00:06:31,791 --> 00:06:33,083
[door creaking]

90
00:06:33,166 --> 00:06:35,541
You want me to quit
and raise her full-time?

91
00:06:35,625 --> 00:06:37,000
That's a possibility.

92
00:06:38,458 --> 00:06:40,333
And you could earn enough to feed us?

93
00:06:41,416 --> 00:06:44,500
[door creaking]

94
00:06:46,625 --> 00:06:47,458
[mother gasps]

95
00:06:48,250 --> 00:06:49,416
Mom.

96
00:06:50,041 --> 00:06:51,041
[mother crying softly]

97
00:06:53,458 --> 00:06:55,458
[somber music playing]

98
00:07:00,125 --> 00:07:01,000
[mother sniffles]

99
00:07:02,291 --> 00:07:03,250
[glass crunches]

100
00:07:04,583 --> 00:07:06,583
[mother continues crying]

101
00:07:10,583 --> 00:07:11,583
[sobbing]

102
00:07:18,791 --> 00:07:19,708
[cries out]

103
00:07:27,708 --> 00:07:29,791
Mom, look how pretty this is!

104
00:07:29,875 --> 00:07:32,416
["Goodbye Song" by Byrd & Heart
playing on radio]

105
00:07:33,041 --> 00:07:34,208
Which one do you like?

106
00:07:35,708 --> 00:07:37,625
I don't know. What's your favorite?

107
00:07:37,708 --> 00:07:41,791
- ♪ And you could be right about him too ♪
- I want you to choose.

108
00:07:41,875 --> 00:07:42,708
Whichever.

109
00:07:44,416 --> 00:07:47,291
♪ Loving you was more than I could say ♪

110
00:07:47,375 --> 00:07:49,500
Why did you come? So you can sulk?

111
00:07:49,583 --> 00:07:52,083
♪ Or do, but will you still… ♪

112
00:07:52,166 --> 00:07:53,916
I'm here now. Isn't that enough?

113
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:56,041
♪ …though we're through ♪

114
00:07:57,125 --> 00:07:58,500
I didn't force you to come.

115
00:07:58,583 --> 00:08:00,166
♪ When you said goodbye… ♪

116
00:08:00,250 --> 00:08:02,250
[Wat] This is hopeless. Let's turn back.

117
00:08:04,083 --> 00:08:05,750
Fine, turn around.

118
00:08:05,833 --> 00:08:08,333
I don't want to go home.
I want to go to the sea!

119
00:08:10,541 --> 00:08:11,375
Okay, dear.

120
00:08:12,458 --> 00:08:15,583
♪ For the last time, let me say… ♪

121
00:08:15,666 --> 00:08:17,916
At least try and pretend to be happy.

122
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:23,791
♪ And so I sing this goodbye song to you ♪

123
00:08:23,875 --> 00:08:24,750
Pull over.

124
00:08:24,833 --> 00:08:28,250
- ♪ You would not see my love… ♪
- What now?

125
00:08:28,333 --> 00:08:30,666
- I said pull over! Stop the car!
- What are you doing? Don't!

126
00:08:30,750 --> 00:08:32,416
[Wat] Are you crazy?! Stop it!

127
00:08:40,375 --> 00:08:43,041
[young Varee] Mom, where are you going?
Please stay.

128
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,333
♪ How can I… ♪

129
00:08:47,416 --> 00:08:49,416
- [tires screeching]
- [metal crashing]

130
00:08:50,666 --> 00:08:52,875
♪ My only love has gone ♪

131
00:08:52,958 --> 00:08:56,416
- ♪ So now I long for yesterday ♪
- Varee! [gasps]

132
00:08:56,500 --> 00:09:00,666
- ♪ And so I play this goodbye song ♪
- [mother wails]

133
00:09:00,750 --> 00:09:02,750
♪ To you ♪

134
00:09:05,666 --> 00:09:08,541
[opening theme song playing]

135
00:09:57,458 --> 00:10:04,291
DON'T COME HOME

136
00:10:04,375 --> 00:10:06,708
[fire crackling]

137
00:10:06,791 --> 00:10:09,041
[mother] March 14, 1991.

138
00:10:10,375 --> 00:10:12,708
March 14, 1991.

139
00:10:15,250 --> 00:10:17,083
March 14, 1991.

140
00:10:17,166 --> 00:10:18,791
TAKUA PA POWER PLANT

141
00:10:18,875 --> 00:10:21,500
[mother] March 14, 1991.

142
00:10:22,250 --> 00:10:25,125
MISS VAREE JARUKANANT

143
00:10:25,208 --> 00:10:27,250
[mournful music playing]

144
00:10:27,333 --> 00:10:29,875
[psychiatrist] Have you taken
the medication I've given you?

145
00:10:33,291 --> 00:10:35,333
And have you had any sleep?

146
00:10:36,958 --> 00:10:37,791
[groans softly]

147
00:10:44,833 --> 00:10:47,000
We're leaving now. Good night, ma'am.

148
00:10:51,375 --> 00:10:53,541
March 14, 1991.

149
00:10:54,416 --> 00:10:57,541
[cries] March 14, 1991.

150
00:10:57,625 --> 00:11:00,875
[sobbing] March 14, 1991.

151
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:03,750
[psychiatrist] What is that?

152
00:11:07,750 --> 00:11:10,250
[breathing heavily, sobs]

153
00:11:10,333 --> 00:11:11,250
[mother] The day.

154
00:11:13,958 --> 00:11:18,250
The day my daughter and my husband died.

155
00:11:21,833 --> 00:11:23,750
Are you ready to talk about it?

156
00:11:26,916 --> 00:11:28,625
What's the point of talking?

157
00:11:30,166 --> 00:11:32,666
Is talking going to
bring back my daughter?

158
00:11:35,916 --> 00:11:38,791
The person I want to bring back is you.

159
00:11:41,583 --> 00:11:43,791
What happened was an accident.

160
00:11:45,166 --> 00:11:47,083
No one wanted this thing to happen.

161
00:11:48,083 --> 00:11:50,041
Nothing is going to happen…

162
00:11:52,458 --> 00:11:54,458
until something moves.

163
00:11:56,791 --> 00:11:58,000
And what happened…

164
00:11:58,666 --> 00:11:59,750
[sobs]

165
00:11:59,833 --> 00:12:01,458
…was because of me.

166
00:12:01,541 --> 00:12:04,666
[sobbing]

167
00:12:06,125 --> 00:12:08,458
Because I'm an evil mother.

168
00:12:08,541 --> 00:12:10,541
[sobbing continues]

169
00:12:15,750 --> 00:12:17,375
I understand you feel that way.

170
00:12:19,250 --> 00:12:23,125
You must remember
we can't go back to correct the past.

171
00:12:24,666 --> 00:12:25,958
I want you to let go.

172
00:12:27,416 --> 00:12:29,458
I can't turn back time.

173
00:12:31,166 --> 00:12:32,833
That's why I can't let go.

174
00:12:34,541 --> 00:12:36,875
How dare you tell me to let go!

175
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:39,250
[sighs tearfully]

176
00:12:40,666 --> 00:12:43,291
I made my daughter die.

177
00:12:44,708 --> 00:12:46,875
[inhales sharply] I killed her.

178
00:12:47,833 --> 00:12:50,125
[sobbing]

179
00:12:53,291 --> 00:12:55,291
- [water lapping]
- [birds chirping]

180
00:13:00,041 --> 00:13:03,375
- [dark music playing]
- [mother whimpering]

181
00:13:05,250 --> 00:13:06,083
[grunts in pain]

182
00:13:22,416 --> 00:13:23,416
[grunts angrily]

183
00:13:25,708 --> 00:13:28,250
[groaning]

184
00:13:31,583 --> 00:13:34,333
[panting, whimpering]

185
00:13:36,375 --> 00:13:38,083
[wind whistling]

186
00:13:38,166 --> 00:13:40,166
[dark music intensifies]

187
00:13:43,916 --> 00:13:47,208
[electricity crackling]

188
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:50,833
[gasps]

189
00:13:58,375 --> 00:14:00,375
[panting]

190
00:14:05,875 --> 00:14:06,708
[gasps]

191
00:14:09,041 --> 00:14:10,583
[dramatic music building]

192
00:14:10,666 --> 00:14:12,666
- [music fades out]
- [insects chirping]

193
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:19,166
What's your project?

194
00:14:20,083 --> 00:14:21,791
Why such a huge generator?

195
00:14:26,916 --> 00:14:28,916
[mysterious music playing]

196
00:14:50,208 --> 00:14:52,958
MARCH 14, 1991

197
00:14:59,375 --> 00:15:02,291
- [gear clanks]
- [intriguing music playing]

198
00:15:05,291 --> 00:15:07,166
- [electricity buzzing]
- [mother gasps]

199
00:15:08,750 --> 00:15:09,666
[gear clanks]

200
00:15:09,750 --> 00:15:11,750
[distant siren wailing]

201
00:15:14,833 --> 00:15:16,833
[lightbulbs buzzing]

202
00:15:24,708 --> 00:15:26,458
[electricity crackling]

203
00:15:27,375 --> 00:15:30,583
[thrilling music playing]

204
00:15:54,583 --> 00:15:57,625
Fourteenth of March, 1991.

205
00:15:57,708 --> 00:16:00,166
Fourteenth of March, 1991.

206
00:16:00,250 --> 00:16:04,500
- Fourteenth of March, 1991.
- [generator powering up]

207
00:16:04,583 --> 00:16:07,458
Fourteenth of March, 1991.

208
00:16:08,958 --> 00:16:10,375
[generator powering down]

209
00:16:10,458 --> 00:16:11,333
[mother whimpers]

210
00:16:13,708 --> 00:16:15,208
[screams in anger]

211
00:16:15,291 --> 00:16:18,041
[sobbing]

212
00:16:19,500 --> 00:16:21,750
[screaming in anger]

213
00:16:23,958 --> 00:16:25,250
[continues screaming]

214
00:16:25,750 --> 00:16:27,208
[sobs]

215
00:16:33,208 --> 00:16:37,375
- [sobbing, screaming]
- [pounding generator]

216
00:16:41,250 --> 00:16:42,666
[electricity crackling]

217
00:16:43,791 --> 00:16:45,833
- [screaming]
- [pounding generator]

218
00:16:47,666 --> 00:16:49,833
[electricity crackling]

219
00:17:02,833 --> 00:17:04,833
[intense music playing]

220
00:17:22,166 --> 00:17:24,166
[generator powering down]

221
00:17:25,958 --> 00:17:28,333
[mother breathing shakily]

222
00:17:39,125 --> 00:17:40,500
[tender music playing]

223
00:17:40,583 --> 00:17:42,583
[birds chirping]

224
00:17:53,333 --> 00:17:54,166
Mom?

225
00:17:56,916 --> 00:17:59,458
[mother] You're awake. You've woken up.

226
00:18:00,666 --> 00:18:01,916
Is Mom here?

227
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:03,416
I want Mom.

228
00:18:04,125 --> 00:18:05,583
Mom! [whimpers]

229
00:18:07,750 --> 00:18:08,708
Mom!

230
00:18:09,333 --> 00:18:11,333
[Min crying]

231
00:18:11,416 --> 00:18:12,250
Mom!

232
00:18:13,583 --> 00:18:15,333
Are you here? Mom?

233
00:18:16,291 --> 00:18:19,000
[crying]

234
00:18:22,125 --> 00:18:23,375
Mom?

235
00:18:24,666 --> 00:18:25,500
Mom!

236
00:18:27,916 --> 00:18:28,750
Mom!

237
00:18:30,958 --> 00:18:33,250
[crying] Mom?

238
00:18:36,708 --> 00:18:37,541
Mom!

239
00:18:44,375 --> 00:18:45,750
Don't run. You'll fall.

240
00:18:47,666 --> 00:18:48,583
[Min] Mom!

241
00:18:48,666 --> 00:18:50,750
[insects chirping]

242
00:18:50,833 --> 00:18:52,791
- [mournful string music playing]
- Mom!

243
00:18:53,791 --> 00:18:55,791
[crying]

244
00:18:56,541 --> 00:18:59,000
Mom! [sobbing]

245
00:18:59,083 --> 00:19:01,208
- [mother] Little girl, don't cry.
- Mom! [sobbing]

246
00:19:01,291 --> 00:19:02,250
[mother] Don't cry.

247
00:19:02,333 --> 00:19:05,333
[Min sobbing] I want my mom.

248
00:19:09,208 --> 00:19:12,208
- Your clothes are all dirty. Come.
- [Min sobbing]

249
00:19:17,583 --> 00:19:18,625
Tell me your name.

250
00:19:20,916 --> 00:19:23,541
My name is Min. Mintira.

251
00:19:24,583 --> 00:19:27,333
- And how old are you?
- I'm five.

252
00:19:40,291 --> 00:19:41,958
This should fit you nicely.

253
00:19:43,250 --> 00:19:44,625
Put this on for now.

254
00:19:44,708 --> 00:19:46,875
I'll take you
to buy some new clothes later.

255
00:19:52,916 --> 00:19:54,916
We're going on a little trip into town.

256
00:19:56,125 --> 00:19:58,875
I'm going to buy you some nice clothes.
Just for you.

257
00:19:58,958 --> 00:20:00,958
[gentle music playing]

258
00:20:05,208 --> 00:20:07,208
[indistinct chattering]

259
00:20:11,083 --> 00:20:11,916
Come.

260
00:20:15,583 --> 00:20:16,500
Good afternoon.

261
00:20:17,500 --> 00:20:19,000
Let's take a look, okay?

262
00:20:25,250 --> 00:20:26,208
[mother chuckles]

263
00:20:27,666 --> 00:20:31,083
TAKUA PA BOUTIQUE

264
00:20:41,208 --> 00:20:42,583
How old is your daughter?

265
00:20:44,541 --> 00:20:46,333
Oh! She's not my…

266
00:20:55,166 --> 00:20:56,166
She's five.

267
00:20:56,958 --> 00:20:58,875
A beauty like her mother.

268
00:21:01,208 --> 00:21:02,041
Thanks.

269
00:21:07,958 --> 00:21:09,250
DOLLS FOR KIDS

270
00:21:10,166 --> 00:21:11,708
I used to play with this.

